d and America, large numbers of Irish Americans enlisted. However, as the war progressed, the Emancipation Proclamation, federal draft, and sharp rise in casualties caused Irish Americans to question-and sometimes abandon-the war effort because they viewed such changes as detrimental to their families and futures in America and Ireland.By recognizing these competing and often fluid loyalties, The Harp and the Eagle sheds new light on the relationship between Irish-American volunteers and the Union Army, and how the Irish made sense of both the Civil War and their loyalty to the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCatholicszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrish American soldiersxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrish AmericansxHistoryy19th century. 4aAnalyzing. 4aBruce. 4aCatholics. 4aCivil. 4aIrish-American. 4aSusannah. 4aUnion. 4aUral. 4aWar. 4achurch. 4acivilians. 4acommunity. 4acomplex. 4adiaries. 4adiplomatic. 4aexpands. 4afought. 4aletters. 4amilitary. 4anewspapers. 4apicture. 4arecords. 4areveals. 4asignificantly. 4asoldiers. 4astory. 4athose. 4awritten. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814785744.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK